DateHunter - For those of you with no clock....

	By S.Zoneff

@{"      Introduction    " link intro} - What's it for.
@{"      Installation    " link install} - How to get it going.
@{"      Stuff           " link stuff} - Misc. Information.

@ENDNODE

@NODE intro "Introduction"

This is a small program for people with no battery backed up clock. It
 sits in your WBstartup drawer or user-startup sequence and checks the 
date on bootup. If it finds that the year reported by your clock
is before 1996 , it automatically starts the time prefs so that the 
first thing you see on your WorkBench is the time prefs.. 
THIS MAKES THIS PROGRAM OS2.0 OR GREATER ONLY.

I Originally wrote this program when I upgraded from an A2000 
(that does have a battery backed up clock)
to an A1200 that did not (until I installed an '030 card anyway)

It is very small (only 4K) and does not slow down boot-up. 
It also quits totally after it has checked the date (so does not 
sit in the background steeling CPU cycles).

Because of these 2 points it might be worth sticking it in your WBstartup drawer 
anyway. It can tell you if your clock battery has gone flat (if you have not used 
that Amiga for awhile - you were using your other Amigas instead!) 
Or the clock has been messed with by some other program (E.g. some games would 
change or *disable* the clock on my A2000!)

Remember that this program does nothing if the year your clock reports is 1996 or 
later.

@ENDNODE

@NODE install "How to get it going"

To install it you can either drag the icon into your WBstartup drawer or
put it into your user-startup.

Now that's easy.. 

If you are a PC user then the installation gets a bit more involved Because you must
also install a new brain into your head. Most of you will not need to do this step.

@ENDNODE

